e military and throughout US society. The African American families who tried to adopt Korean-black children also faced and challenged discrimination in the child welfare agencies that arranged adoptions.Drawing on extensive research in black newspapers and magazines, interviews with African American soldiers, and case notes about African American adoptive families, A War Born Family demonstrates how the Cold War and the struggle for civil rights led child welfare agencies to reevaluate African American men and women as suitable adoptive parents, advancing the cause of Korean transnational adoption.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican American families. 0aAfrican American parents. 0aIntercountry adoptionzKorea (South)xHistoryy20th century. 0aIntercountry adoptionzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aInterracial adoptionzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aKorean War, 1950-1953xChildren. 0aRacially mixed childrenzKorea (South). 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh  aAfrican American soldiers.  aCold War civil rights.  aFoster Care and Adoption Project.  aGI children.  aHines Ward Jr.  aInternational Social Service.  aKorean War.  aKorean black children.  aKorean transnational adoption.  aMixed race children.  aNational Urban League.  aPearl S. Buck Foundation.  aPearl S. Buck.  aPost Exchange.  aUS domestic adoption.  aWelcome House.  aWorld War II.  aadoption reform.  ablack press.  achild welfare professionals.  acivil rights.  agender and racial oppression.  agender hierarchies.  ainterracial families.  amixed-race Koreans.  aproxy adoption.  asocial welfare.  atransnational adoption.  atransracial adoption.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBoo